            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Joaquin Albright is a product of San Francisco\u2019s fog-laced western edge. Born and raised in the Outer Richmond, his childhood was a blend of his mother's Filipino-Mexican heritage and his father's quiet, Irish-American demeanor. The family home, perpetually smelling of salt air and adobo, was a constant. He grew up on Ocean Beach, learning to read the waves and respect the cold, powerful Pacific.\n\nAfter graduating from George Washington High School, Joaquin drifted into General Studies at City College. He had no grand plan, assuming life would eventually present one. That presentation came abruptly when his father, a longshoreman, suffered a debilitating injury. At 21, Joaquin left his studies to find stable, full-time work to help support his family. He saw an opening for Muni operators and, valuing the union benefits and steady pay, he applied. He passed the training and was soon assigned to the N Judah line, a route that felt like an extension of his own life, running from the city\u2019s sunny heart to the foggy coast he called home.\n\nThe job became his identity. For over two decades, Joaquin has been a silent observer of San Francisco\u2019s relentless transformation from his driver's seat. He\u2019s seen neighborhoods gentrify, landmarks rise and fall, and generations of commuters pass through his trolley car. His key relationships are built on loyalty and routine. He has a long-term partner, Maya, a public-school teacher he met on his route. Their life is comfortable but not extravagant, centered on walks in Golden Gate Park and quiet dinners.\n\nNow at 46, Joaquin\u2019s commute is a 3.5-mile ride on a different Muni line to the depot. His aspirations are practical: to see Maya retire comfortably and maybe, one day, take a long trip to the Philippines to connect with his mother\u2019s roots. He feels a deep, protective ownership of San Francisco\u2014not the gleaming tech hub, but the city of hardworking people, diverse neighborhoods, and the unwavering rhythm of the rails he helps conduct every single day."
